  "eprint": {
    "title": "IND-CCA-secure Key Encapsulation Mechanism in the Quantum Random Oracle Model, Revisited",
    "authors": [
      {
        "name": "Haodong Jiang",
        "email": "hdjiang13@gmail",
        "affiliation": ""
      },
      {
        "name": "Zhenfeng Zhang",
        "email": "",
        "affiliation": ""
      },
      {
        "name": "Long Chen",
        "email": "",
        "affiliation": ""
      },
      {
        "name": "Hong Wang",
        "email": "",
        "affiliation": ""
      },
      {
        "name": "Zhi Ma",
        "email": "",
        "affiliation": ""
      }
    ],
    "abstract": "With the gradual progress of NIST's post-quantum cryptography standardization, the Round-1 KEM proposals have been posted for public to discuss and evaluate.\nAmong the IND-CCA-secure KEM constructions, mostly, an IND-CPA-secure (or OW-CPA-secure) public-key encryption (PKE) scheme is first introduced, then some generic transformations are applied to it.\nAll these generic transformations are constructed in the random oracle model (ROM).\nTo fully assess the post-quantum security, security analysis in the quantum random oracle model (QROM) is preferred.\nHowever, current works either lacked a QROM security proof or just followed Targhi and Unruh's proof technique (TCC-B 2016) and modified the original transformations by adding an additional hash to the ciphertext to achieve the QROM security.\n\nIn this paper, by using a novel proof technique, we present QROM security reductions for two widely used generic transformations without suffering any ciphertext overhead.\nMeanwhile, the security bounds are much tighter than the ones derived by utilizing Targhi and Unruh's proof technique.\nThus, our QROM security proofs not only provide a solid post-quantum security guarantee for NIST Round-1 KEM schemes, but also\nsimplify the constructions and reduce the ciphertext sizes.\nWe also provide QROM security reductions for Hofheinz-Hoevelmanns-Kiltz modular transformations (TCC 2017), which can help to obtain a variety of combined transformations with different requirements and properties.",
    "keywords": [
      "public-key cryptography",
      "quantum random oracle model",
      "key encapsulation mechanism",
      "IND-CCA security",
      "generic transformation"
    ],
    "category": "Public-key cryptography",
    "publication_info": "A minor revision of an IACR publication in CRYPTO 2018",
    "last_updated": "2019-07-03",
    "license": "CC BY",
    "related_papers": []
  }
